#Text=Polychrome 's Magic

#Text=On this morning , which ought to be the last of this important journey , our friends started away as bright and cheery as could be , and Woot whistled a merry tune so that Polychrome could dance to the music .
#Text=On reaching the top of the hill , the plain spread out before them in all its beauty of blue grasses and wildflowers , and Mount Munch seemed much nearer than it had the previous evening .
#Text=They trudged on at a brisk pace , and by noon the mountain was so close that they could admire its appearance .
#Text=Its slopes were partly clothed with pretty evergreens , and its foot-hills were tufted with a slender waving bluegrass that had a tassel on the end of every blade .

#Text=And , for the first time , they perceived , near the foot of the mountain , a charming house , not of great size but neatly painted and with many flowers surrounding it and vines climbing over the doors and windows .
#Text=It was toward this solitary house that our travelers now directed their steps , thinking to inquire of the people who lived there where Nimmie Amee might be found .

#Text=There were no paths , but the way was quite open and clear , and they were drawing near to the dwelling when Woot the Wanderer , who was then in the lead of the little party , halted with such an abrupt jerk that he stumbled over backward and lay flat on his back in the meadow .
#Text=The Scarecrow stopped to look at the boy .
#Text=" Why did you do that ? " he asked in surprise .
#Text=Woot sat up and gazed around him in amazement .
#Text=" I -- I do n't know ! " he replied .
#Text=The two tin men , arm in arm , started to pass them when both halted and tumbled , with a great clatter , into a heap beside Woot .
#Text=Polychrome , laughing at the absurd sight , came dancing up and she , also , came to a sudden stop , but managed to save herself from falling .
#Text=Everyone of them was much astonished , and the Scarecrow said with a puzzled look :
#Text=" I do n't see anything . "
#Text=" Nor I , " said Woot ; " but something hit me , just the same . "
#Text=" Some invisible person struck me a heavy blow , " declared the Tin Woodman , struggling to separate himself from the Tin Soldier , whose legs and arms were mixed with his own .
#Text=" I 'm not sure it was a person , " said Polychrome , looking more grave than usual .
#Text=" It seems to me that I merely ran into some hard substance which barred my way .

#Text= I can feel something hard -- something smooth as glass , " she said , " but I 'm sure it is not glass . "

column1: #Text=" Let me try , " suggested Woot , getting up ; but when he tried to go forward , he discovered the same barrier that Polychrome had encountered .
#Text=" No , " he said , " it is n't glass .

column3:
_	_	_	_

#Text= Air , " replied a small voice beside him .

column1: #Text=" Solid air ; that 's all . "
#Text=They all looked downward and found a sky-blue rabbit had stuck his head out of a burrow in the ground .
#Text=The rabbit 's eyes were a deeper blue than his fur , and the pretty creature seemed friendly and unafraid .
#Text=" Air ! " exclaimed Woot , staring in astonishment into the rabbit 's blue eyes ;
#Text=" whoever heard of air so solid that one cannot push it aside ? "
#Text=" You ca n't push this air aside , " declared the rabbit , " for it was made hard by powerful sorcery , and it forms a wall that is intended to keep people from getting to that house yonder . "
#Text=" Oh ; it 's a wall , is it ? " said the Tin Woodman .
#Text=" Yes , it is really a wall , " answered the rabbit , " and it is fully six feet thick . "
#Text=" How high is it ? " inquired Captain Fyter , the Tin Soldier .
#Text=" Oh , ever so high ; perhaps a mile , " said the rabbit .
#Text=" Could n't we go around it ? " asked Woot .
#Text=" Of course , for the wall is a circle , " explained the rabbit .
#Text=" In the center of the circle stands the house , so you may walk around the Wall of Solid Air , but you ca n't get to the house . "
#Text=" Who put the air wall around the house ? " was the Scarecrow 's question .
#Text=" Nimmie Amee did that . "
#Text=" Nimmie Amee ! " they all exclaimed in surprise .
#Text=" Yes , " answered the rabbit .

#Text=" She used to live with an old Witch , who was suddenly destroyed , and when Nimmie Amee ran away from the Witch 's house , she took with her just one magic formula -- pure sorcery it was -- which enabled her to build this air wall around her house -- the house yonder .

column3:
_	_	_	_

#Text= Does Nimmie Amee live there now ? " asked the Tin Woodman anxiously .

column1: #Text=" Yes , indeed , " said the rabbit .
#Text=" And does she weep and wail from morning till night ? " continued the Emperor .
#Text=" No ; she seems quite happy , " asserted the rabbit .
#Text=The Tin Woodman seemed quite disappointed to hear this report of his old sweetheart , but the Scarecrow reassured his friend , saying :
#Text=" Never mind , your Majesty ; however happy Nimmie Amee is now , I 'm sure she will be much happier as Empress of the Winkies . "
#Text=" Perhaps , " said Captain Fyter , somewhat stiffly , " she will be still more happy to become the bride of a Tin Soldier . "
